{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526946"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:27:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14171"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14171"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.88,0.04,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6854"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111783"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6854","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6854"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15550"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45746"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111783","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111783"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of exertional dyspnoea and occasional palpitations. He is a competitive swimmer and has noticed a decline in his performance. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His father died suddenly at age 45, but the cause is unknown. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a systolic ejection murmur at the left sternal border that increases with standing and Valsalva maneuver. An electrocardiogram shows left ventricular hypertrophy with deep S waves in V1-V3 and tall R waves in V5-V6.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Exercise stress test","Echocardiography","24-hour Holter monitor","Cardiac MRI","Coronary angiography"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is highly suggestive of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM). The combination of exertional symptoms, family history of sudden cardiac death, and characteristic physical examination findings (systolic murmur that increases with standing and Valsalva) are classic for HCM. The ECG findings of left ventricular hypertrophy further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiography\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. It is the primary imaging modality for diagnosing HCM, allowing visualization of left ventricular hypertrophy, assessment of outflow tract obstruction, and evaluation of systolic and diastolic function. Echocardiography can also help rule out other causes of left ventricular hypertrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoronary angiography\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically indicated as an initial test in young patients with suspected HCM unless there is a strong suspicion of coronary artery disease. This patient\u0027s age and lack of typical angina symptoms make coronary artery disease less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eexercise stress test\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in assessing functional capacity and provocable outflow tract obstruction in HCM patients. However, it is not the first-line diagnostic test and would typically be performed after echocardiography confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E is valuable for detecting arrhythmias in HCM patients, which are common and can contribute to symptoms. However, it is not the initial diagnostic test of choice when HCM is suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac MRI\u003C/strong\u003E provides excellent tissue characterisation and can detect areas of fibrosis in HCM. While it\u0027s a powerful tool in the evaluation of HCM, it is usually reserved for cases where echocardiography is inconclusive or to provide additional information for risk stratification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with echocardiography, management would typically involve beta-blockers to reduce outflow obstruction and improve diastolic function. Risk stratification for sudden cardiac death is crucial, potentially leading to consideration of an implantable cardioverter-defibrillator in high-risk patients. Genetic counselling and screening of first-degree relatives are also important aspects of care in HCM.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy is characterised by left ventricular hypertrophy without an identifiable cause.","Sudden cardiac death is a significant risk in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy, especially in young athletes.","Beta-blockers are first-line treatment for symptomatic hypertrophic cardiomyopathy to reduce outflow obstruction and improve diastolic function."],"references":["2024 AHA/ACC/AMSSM/HRS/PACES/SCMR Guideline for the Management of Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy: A Report of the American Heart Association/American College of Cardiology Joint Committee on Clinical Practice Guidelines"]},